abstract = {{This study theoretically and empirically addresses the possible separation      of substance and symbolism in CEO compensation contracts by examining      political and institutional determinants of long-term incentive plan      (LTIP) adoption and use among 570 of the largest U.S. corporations over      two decades. We find that a substantial number of firms are likely to      adopt but not actually use-or only limitedly use-LTIPs, suggesting a      potential separation of substance and symbol in CEO compensation      contracts. Analyses suggest that this decoupling of LTIP adoption and use      is particularly prevalent in firms with powerful CEOs and firms with poor      prior performance. Further analyses show that whereas early adopters are      more likely to pursue alignment between CEO and shareholder interests      substantively, later adopters may pursue legitimacy by symbolically      controlling agency costs. More generally, the study highlights how      decoupling in organizations can be understood in terms of both      micro-political and macro-institutional forces.}}, 
